   "source": [
    "## Case Study: $CO_2$ Levels\n",
    "\n",
    "As a case study we will look at [$CO_2$ levels, as recorded by the Mauna Loa laboratory](https://gml.noaa.gov/ccgg/trends/).\n",
    "\n",
    "First we'll download and extract the data:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "f6a9bf2e",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-02T08:48:16.449551Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-02T08:48:16.449112Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.233602Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.233057Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from copy import deepcopy\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from matplotlib.axes import Axes\n",
    "\n",
    "import gpflow"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "41e6f3ce",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.235786Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.235534Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.837102Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.836551Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "co2_data = pd.read_csv(\n",
    "    \"https://gml.noaa.gov/webdata/ccgg/trends/co2/co2_mm_mlo.csv\", comment=\"#\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "co2_data = co2_data[co2_data[\"decimal date\"] > 1990]\n",
    "Xco2 = co2_data[\"decimal date\"].values[:, None]\n",
    "Yco2 = co2_data[\"average\"].values[:, None]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8c7955ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And then we'll define a helper function to plot our kernel against the $CO_2$ data:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "384a8e14",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.839189Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.839029Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.844645Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-02T08:48:19.844112Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_co2_model_prediction(\n",
    "    ax: Axes, model: gpflow.models.GPModel, start: float, stop: float\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    Xplot = np.linspace(start, stop, 200)[:, None]\n",
    "    idx_plot = (start < Xco2) & (Xco2 < stop)\n",
    "\n",
    "    f_mean, f_var = model.predict_f(Xplot, full_cov=False)\n",
    "    f_lower = f_mean - 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "    f_upper = f_mean + 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xco2[idx_plot], Yco2[idx_plot], \"kx\", mew=2)\n",
    "    (mean_line,) = ax.plot(Xplot, f_mean, \"-\")\n",
    "    color = mean_line.get_color()\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_lower, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_upper, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.fill_between(Xplot[:, 0], f_lower[:, 0], f_upper[:, 0], color=color, alpha=0.1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_co2_kernel(kernel: gpflow.kernels.Kernel) -> None:\n",
    "    model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "        (Xco2, Yco2),\n",
    "        kernel=deepcopy(kernel),\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "    l = opt.minimize(\n",
    "        model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=1000)\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    # print(l)\n",
    "    # gpflow.utilities.print_summary(model, \"notebook\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)\n",
    "    plot_co2_model_prediction(ax1, model, 1950, 2050)\n",
    "    plot_co2_model_prediction(ax2, model, 2015, 2030)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0147b999",
   "metadata": {},

    "On the left side is a plot of our entire time range. On the right side we zoom in to the 2015-2030 range.\n",
    "\n",
    "Our model clearly picks up the general trend of the data, but I see two problems:\n",
    "* It doesn't pick up the periodic anual trend.\n",
    "* When we look at our predictions for 2050, it doesn't seem to continue the upwards trend of the data."
